body:
@snippins  Ohhh that makes sense. You're right, there needs to be a mainloop running for the whole thing to work. I've actually looked into the GLib source code and [DBusMenuModel asks for the main context](https://github.com/GNOME/glib/blob/f924d0b1f7d2b019f1abb56685dcfda74266c608/gio/gdbusmenumodel.c#L886). When looking for the path, it [doesn't find it](https://github.com/GNOME/glib/blob/f924d0b1f7d2b019f1abb56685dcfda74266c608/gio/gdbusmenumodel.c#L321) and creates it. But that path is not linked to the actual menu on the bus.

This is also the first time for me having to work with GLib, so I'm also pretty clueless about whether there's a way to bypass this. What I think we have to do is query an arbitrary signal, enter the mainloop, use the signal to trigger menu-discovery, and exit with quit().

What do you mean with 'almost'? Does it crash for you or not? I found that crashes seem to be pretty arbitrary and dependent on the time between opening a new window and running Start(), but when 'stress'-testing, I crash pretty consistantly.
